03717nam a22005295i 9780520933699DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20072007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209336997 a10.1525/97805209336992doi  a(DE-B1597)519315  a(OCoLC)558876160  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML195b.B47 2007eb 7aMUS0060002bisacsh04a780.9/0332221 aBerger, Karol, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBach's Cycle, Mozart's Arrow :bAn Essay on the Origins of Musical Modernity /cKarol Berger. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (444 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tPrelude: L'Orfeo, or the Anxiety of the Moderns -- tPart I. Bach's Cycle -- tPart II. Mozart's Arrow -- tPostlude: Between Utopia and Melancholy -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this erudite and elegantly composed argument, Karol Berger uses the works of Monteverdi, Bach, Mozart, and Beethoven to support two groundbreaking claims: first, that it was only in the later eighteenth century that music began to take the flow of time from the past to the future seriously; second, that this change in the structure of musical time was an aspect of a larger transformation in the way educated Europeans began to imagine and think about time with the onset of modernity, a part of a shift from the premodern Christian outlook to the modern post-Christian worldview. Until this historical moment, as Berger illustrates in his analysis of Bach's St. Matthew Passion, music was simply "in time." Its successive events unfolded one after another, but the distinction between past and future, earlier and later, was not central to the way the music was experienced and understood. But after the shift, as he finds in looking at Mozart's Don Giovanni, the experience of linear time is transformed into music's essential subject matter; the cycle of time unbends and becomes an arrow. Berger complements these musical case studies with a rich survey of the philosophical, theological, and literary trends influencing artists during this period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMusicxHistory and criticismx18th century. 0aMusicy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933699423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520933699.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles